One of the biggest and most famous examples of law in action is the concept of Miranda Rights, which stems from the historic US Supreme Court case Miranda v. Arizona (1966).This single law completely changed how police around the world handle arrests and how human rights are protected during criminal investigations.🚨 The Real-Life Story Behind the LawIn 1963, a man named Ernesto Miranda was arrested by the police in Arizona.The Issue: The police interrogated Miranda for two hours without telling him that he had the right to remain silent, or that he had the right to a lawyer.The Result: Confused and intimidated, Miranda signed a written confession admitting to the crime.The Legal Battle: Miranda's lawyer argued that the confession should not be allowed in court because the police never informed Miranda of his constitutional rights. The case went all the way to the Supreme Court.
